<subSubSection lastPageId="11" lastPageNumber="323" pageId="10" pageNumber="322" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="10.[816,1429,1060,1458]" box="[816,955,1060,1086]" pageId="10" pageNumber="322">
<emphasis box="[816,955,1060,1086]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="322">Description</emphasis>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="10.[816,1429,1060,1458]" lastBlockId="11.[159,771,220,381]" lastPageId="11" lastPageNumber="323" pageId="10" pageNumber="322">
A very small species of slit-faced bat with a forearm length of 
<quantity box="[982,1090,1127,1153]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.5799999999999996" pageId="10" pageNumber="322" unit="mm" value="35.8">35.8 mm</quantity>
. The face is characterised by a noseleaf which comprises two flaps of skin, which give the impression of a slit running down the length of the muzzle. For 
<taxonomicName box="[1045,1143,1229,1255]" class="Mammalia" family="Nycteridae" genus="Nycteris" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="322" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1045,1143,1229,1255]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="322">Nycteris</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, the ears of this species are relatively short and the tragus has a smooth, curved, outer margin (
<figureCitation box="[1090,1188,1296,1322]" captionStart="FIG" captionStartId="10.[159,172,1966,1987]" captionTargetBox="[364,1229,1530,1948]" captionTargetId="figure@10.[322,1290,1525,1958]" captionTargetPageId="10" captionText="FIG. 7. Nycteris hispida, HZM.52.40188. (A): Anterior, left mandible; (B): left, upper incisors and canine; (C): right tragus; (D): baculum (dorsal view [left] and lateral view [right]). Scales for A, B, and D = 1 mm; scale for C = 2 mm" figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3943577" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3943577/files/figure.png" pageId="10" pageNumber="322">Fig. 7C</figureCitation>
). The skull is short (damaged in this specimen) and the upper toothrow (C–M 
<superScript attach="left" box="[886,896,1360,1378]" fontSize="8" pageId="10" pageNumber="322">3</superScript>
) is 
<quantity box="[948,1057,1364,1390]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="5.58" pageId="10" pageNumber="322" unit="mm" value="5.58">5.58 mm</quantity>
in length. Both the upper and lower incisors are trifid (
<figureCitation box="[1110,1281,1398,1424]" captionStart="FIG" captionStartId="10.[159,172,1966,1987]" captionTargetBox="[364,1229,1530,1948]" captionTargetId="figure@10.[322,1290,1525,1958]" captionTargetPageId="10" captionText="FIG. 7. Nycteris hispida, HZM.52.40188. (A): Anterior, left mandible; (B): left, upper incisors and canine; (C): right tragus; (D): baculum (dorsal view [left] and lateral view [right]). Scales for A, B, and D = 1 mm; scale for C = 2 mm" figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3943577" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3943577/files/figure.png" pageId="10" pageNumber="322">Fig. 7A and B</figureCitation>
). The posterior lower premolar is small (
<figureCitation box="[1160,1255,1432,1458]" captionStart="FIG" captionStartId="10.[159,172,1966,1987]" captionTargetBox="[364,1229,1530,1948]" captionTargetId="figure@10.[322,1290,1525,1958]" captionTargetPageId="10" captionText="FIG. 7. Nycteris hispida, HZM.52.40188. (A): Anterior, left mandible; (B): left, upper incisors and canine; (C): right tragus; (D): baculum (dorsal view [left] and lateral view [right]). Scales for A, B, and D = 1 mm; scale for C = 2 mm" figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3943577" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3943577/files/figure.png" pageId="10" pageNumber="322">Fig. 7A</figureCitation>
). The baculum is 3.0 mm in length and characteristically hooked at the tip, with a slender, curved shaft and a slightly bilobate base (
<figureCitation box="[335,432,287,313]" captionStart="FIG" captionStartId="10.[159,172,1966,1987]" captionTargetBox="[364,1229,1530,1948]" captionTargetId="figure@10.[322,1290,1525,1958]" captionTargetPageId="10" captionText="FIG. 7. Nycteris hispida, HZM.52.40188. (A): Anterior, left mandible; (B): left, upper incisors and canine; (C): right tragus; (D): baculum (dorsal view [left] and lateral view [right]). Scales for A, B, and D = 1 mm; scale for C = 2 mm" figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3943577" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3943577/files/figure.png" pageId="11" pageNumber="323">Fig. 7D</figureCitation>
); for comparison with other African 
<taxonomicName box="[257,355,321,347]" class="Mammalia" family="Nycteridae" genus="Nycteris" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="11" pageNumber="323" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[257,355,321,347]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="323">Nycteris</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
taxa see 
<bibRefCitation author="Thomas" box="[468,719,321,347]" etAl="et al." firstAuthor="Thomas" pageId="11" pageNumber="323" pagination="17 - 31" refId="ref14653" refString="THOMAS, N. M., D. L. HARRISON, and P. J. J. BATES. 1994. A study of the baculum in the genus Nycteris (Mammalia, Chiroptera, Nycteridae) with consideration of its taxonomic importance. Bonner zoologische Beitrage, 45: 17 - 31." type="journal article" year="1994">
Thomas 
<emphasis box="[572,632,321,347]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="323">et al.</emphasis>
(1994)
</bibRefCitation>
and 
<bibRefCitation author="Happold and Happold" box="[159,509,355,381]" firstAuthor="Happold" pageId="11" pageNumber="323" refId="ref13898" refString="HAPPOLD, M., and D. C. D. HAPPOLD (eds.). 2013. Mammals of Africa Volume IV: Hedgehogs, shrews, and bats. Bloomsbury Publishing, London, 800 pp." type="book" year="2013">Happold and Happold (2013)</bibRefCitation>
.
</paragraph>
